    "description": "MagicLab MagicBot Z1 Standard Humanoid RobotMagicBot G1 is a full-size humanoid robot developed by MagicLab (also presented in some materials as Magic Atom / MagicLab Robot Technology, Wuxi). Positioned for industrial assistance, logistics, education/research, and customer-facing services, the G1 pairs a human-scale bipedal platform with dexterous hands, onboard AI compute, and modern wireless connectivity. Third-party catalogs and regional resellers consistently describe the model as a 42 active degrees-of-freedom (DoF) humanoid capable of 4–5 hours of operation per battery cycle and 20 kg total payload handling, with headline features aimed at lifelike movement and task versatility. Human-scale form factor Listings for MagicBot G1 (Gen1) describe a standing size around 174 × 58 × 28 cm and a mass near 67.5 kg, aligning the body plan with common human reach envelopes while keeping total weight manageable for indoor floors and elevators. The platform exposes 42 active DoF, supporting expressive upper-body gestures and stable whole-body control for tasks like sorting, carrying, or guided interaction. Dexterous manipulation G1 is frequently marketed with a proprietary “Magic-Hand” and high-torque joint modules for fine-grained manipulation, a focus that shows up in demo language spanning industrial pick-and-place to household or retail interactions. These hands are intended to bridge the gap between simple parallel grippers and research-grade anthropomorphic hands, while keeping service robustness. Connectivity and fleet integration To fit modern sites, G1 supports Wi-Fi 6, 4G/5G, and Bluetooth 5.2. In multi-robot scenarios, MagicNet provides map sharing, job scheduling, and fault tolerance, and can integrate with MES so supervisors can assign tasks and ingest telemetry at fleet scale. Developer- and operator-oriented design Retail and catalog pages highlight open development pathways (SDK/“open source” in some listings) and emphasize industrial, logistics, and collaborative use, plus education and research. Together with 5-hour advertised runtime and 20 kg total payload, the positioning aims at practical trials in labs, factories, hotels, and exhibitions. Technology and Specifications Mechatronics and kinematics Degrees of freedom: 42 active DoF, enabling arm-hand dexterity and head/torso expressiveness. Dimensions & mass: 174 × 58 × 28 cm (standing), ~67.5 kg mass. Payload: ~20 kg total handling capacity (class-appropriate for light industrial and service chores). Power and runtime Battery: ~25 Ah (≈1.35 kWh) advertised pack. Operating time: ~4–5 hours, dependent on gait speed, manipulation duty cycle, and comms. Compute and sensing Onboard compute: dual 8-core CPUs with stated ~100 TOPS AI throughput (edge inference for perception and policy control). Comms: Wi-Fi 6 / 4G/5G / Bluetooth 5.2. Control: materials reference dynamic walking and precise motion control for biped gait and arm trajectories. (Sensor SKUs are not exhaustively listed in public sheets.) Software and fleet layer Software packaging: Some catalogs mark “Open Source” software type, while others present a commercial SDK; buyers should confirm license and access level for their configuration. MagicNet: for multi-robot map sharing, task scheduling, fault tolerance, and MES connectivity in production settings. Applications and Use Cases Manufacturing and light assembly With human-like reach and 20 kg handling, G1 targets machine tending, bin picking/kitting, quality checks, and tool-assisted tasks at workbenches. The humanoid form factor can fit existing fixtures and ergonomics where arms alone are insufficient. Logistics and warehousing Humanoid demonstrations emphasize accurate grasping and carrying of totes, shelf interaction, and scanner-based identification, complementing AMRs in put-wall or exception handling flows. Fleet orchestration via MagicNet supports task queues and hand-offs with other robots. Services and public venues Resellers position G1 for front-of-house experiences (greeting, ushering), booth/exhibition engagement, and back-of-house chores (clearing, restocking) where social acceptability and dexterity matter more than heavy payloads. Education and research The combination of bipedal locomotion, manipulation, and edge AI makes G1 a platform for HRI, planning, and manipulation research, with catalogs noting developer access and multi-scenario support. Advantages / Benefits Human-environment compatibility: Human-scale reach and 42-DoF articulation allow the robot to use existing spaces and tools without major retrofits. Balanced spec sheet: 20 kg payload and 4–5 h runtime are pragmatic for pilot deployments in factories and campuses. Modern connectivity & fleet tools: Wi-Fi 6/5G plus MagicNet give operators options for campus-wide orchestration and MES data flows. Dexterous hands: The Magic-Hand concept focuses on fine manipulation, extending beyond simple grippers for service tasks. FAQ Section What is MagicLab MagicBot G1?MagicBot G1 is a full-size humanoid robot (≈42 DoF) designed for industrial assistance, logistics, education/research, and customer-facing service scenarios. How does MagicBot G1 work?G1 pairs bipedal locomotion and dexterous hands with onboard AI compute (~100 TOPS) and Wi-Fi 6/4G-5G connectivity. In fleets, MagicNet enables shared maps and scheduled tasks with MES integration. Why is MagicBot G1 important?It represents a deployable, human-scale platform that can handle light industrial and service tasks while integrating into enterprise networks and factory software, reducing barriers from lab demo to pilot deployment. What are the key specifications?Approx. 42 DoF, 174 × 58 × 28 cm, ~67.5 kg, 20 kg payload, 25 Ah (≈1.35 kWh) battery for ~4–5 hours, Wi-Fi 6/4G/5G/Bluetooth 5.2, and dynamic walking/precise motion control. Is the software open source?One manufacturer-verified catalog labels the software “Open Source,” while others present commercial SDKs. Confirm with the seller which software package and access level apply to your order. Summary MagicLab’s MagicBot G1 is a 42-DoF, human-scale humanoid aimed at turning embodied-AI research into practical pilots across factories, warehouses, campuses, and public venues. With 20 kg class payload, 4–5 hour runtime, modern Wi-Fi 6/5G connectivity, and the MagicNet fleet layer for map sharing and MES integration, it addresses both the robot and the system problems of deployment. Pricing is broadly listed near US $119,800 for the Standard Edition, with specifics set by configuration and support—placing G1 among the more accessible full-size humanoids for organizations ready to experiment with real-world use cases.",
